  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Syria Crisis Response</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The project aims to better equip humanitarian actors operating in Jordan to integrate the specific needs of the most vulnerable populations affected by the Syria crisis, and to increase the income of extremely vulnerable Syrian refugee families so that they can better meet their basic needs.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="4">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The proposed activities will target a large number of unregistered Syrian refugees thus allowing them to receive needed emergency assistance. Provision of regular cash assistance is seen as a way to tackle this issue for Syrian not being able to work officially in Jordan. The program will therefore proceed to the identification and provision of cash transfers to new Syrian and Jordanian families.

Plans going forward include some community and camp based protection activities with the establishment of community and camp based referral and advocacy networks. Each network will be made up of male and female older people and people with disabilities from the host and the Syrian refugee communities. Members of the networks will be trained on identification of age and disability-related vulnerabilities, information on services rights and entitlements, available referral networks, and advocacy skills to support engagement with humanitarian actors. The protection coordinator will provide support and ensure the participation of some members of the networks in advocacy and/or training activities for humanitarian actors.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="3">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">older refugees, refugees with disabilities</narrative>
  </description>
